04775nam a22006135i 9780271084091DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710840917 a10.1515/97802710840912doi  a(DE-B1597)584380  a(OCoLC)1262308096  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL1080202bisacsh04a274.45/32012231 aFlexsenhar III, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChristians in Caesar's Household :bThe Emperors' Slaves in the Makings of Christianity /cMichael Flexsenhar III. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b17 illustrations/2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInventing Christianity ;v100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Paul, the Philippians, and Caesar's Household (Phil 4:22) -- t2 Paul, Peter, and Nero's Slaves: Martyrdoms and Apostolic Acts -- t3 Rome's Imperial Household in Christian Polemic and Apologetic -- t4 Christian Piety and a Martyred Slave of Caesar -- t5 Material Evidence for a Christian Imperial Freedman -- t6 Christians and Imperial Personnel in Rome's Catacombs -- tConclusion: The Memory of Imperial Slavery in Early Christianity -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume, Michael Flexsenhar III advances the argument that imperial slaves and freedpersons in the Roman Empire were essential to early Christians' self-conception as a distinct people in the Mediterranean and played a multifaceted role in the making of early Christianity.Scholarship in early Christianity has for centuries viewed Roman emperors' slaves and freedmen as responsible for ushering Christianity onto the world stage, traditionally using Paul's allusion to "the saints from Caesar's household" in Philippians 4:22 as a core literary lens. Merging textual and material evidence with diaspora and memory studies, Flexsenhar expands on this narrative to explore new and more nuanced representations of this group, showing how the long-accepted stories of Christian slaves and freepersons in Caesar's household should not be taken at face value but should instead be understood within the context of Christian myth- and meaning-making. Flexsenhar analyzes textual and material evidence from the first to the sixth century, spanning Roman Asia, the Aegean rim, Gaul, and the coast of North Africa as well as the imperial capital itself. As a result, this book shows how stories of the emperor's slaves were integral to key developments in the spread of Christianity, generating origin myths in Rome and establishing a shared history and geography there, differentiating and negotiating assimilation with other groups, and expressing commemorative language, ritual acts, and a material culture.With its thoughtful critical readings of literary and material sources and its fresh analysis of the lived experiences of imperial slaves and freedpersons, Christians in Caesar's Household is indispensable reading for scholars of early Christianity, the origins of religion, and the Roman Empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aRELIGION / Christian Church / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271084091zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271084091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271084091.jpg  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_PLT